title: Tighter coronavirus restrictions, not U.S. elections, are the 'biggest near term risk': UBS
text: "Forget about the U.S. elections or fiscal stimulus — restrictions creeping higher is the single biggest near term risk to the outlook," Arend Kapteyn of UBS wrote in a note.

title: A 'blue wave' in U.S. elections could bring forward Fed rate hikes, says Morgan Stanley
text: The first rate hike by the Federal Reserve could be brought forward from around 2024-2025 to 2023-2024, said Jim Caron, a fixed income portfolio manager at Morgan Stanley Investment Management.

title: Virus Fears And The VIX At 30
text: A new third wave of coronavirus should cause pause for investors looking at taking on new equity positions.

title: House Speaker Pelosi says democrats will continue negotiating Covid relief bill
text: House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin continue their talks on the coronavirus relief package. CNBC's Kayla Tausche joins Shep Smith to discuss.

title: 2020 Remaining Market Outlook (Leading Up To Election Day And Beyond)
text: Individual investors appear to be getting skittish ahead of Election Day.

title: Financial Engineering: Some Long-Term Consequences
text: The corporate world, over the past forty years or so, has been thriving on debt as government policymakers have inflated credit to keep the unemployment rate low.

title: Cramer on building a Biden portfolio: China, solar and cannabis stocks
text: Most stocks that work under Trump will also work under Biden, and vice versa, the "Mad Money" host said.

title: Markets Rise Despite Google Antitrust Suit
text: The lawsuit claimed Google's parent, Alphabet, has a monopoly on search advertising and forces its Google app onto mobile phones.

title: Stock futures rise as stimulus talks continue
text: Stock futures rose in overnight trading after lawmakers said stimulus talks will continue.

title: Stimulus Talks Cause Market Heartburn (Technically Speaking For 10/20)
text: Philadelphia Fed President Harker explains the Fed's new inflation policy.

title: Stock Markets Finish Higher Tuesday, GM Goes Electric, Uber Sees Higher Costs
text: Solid gains gave Wall Street a partial recovery.

title: Stimulus, Politics, and Covid Continue to Move Markets
text: Equities had a choppy week, whipped around by the resurgence of a new factor into the prevailing back and forth between stimulus and politics: the coronavirus. Rising case counts and quasi-lockdowns in much of Western Europe drove international developed markets to underperform (MXEA -1.5%). U.S. markets (SPX) and emerging markets (MXEF) were neck-and-neck, each up 0.2% [Figure 1].

title: Mario Gabelli sees 'extraordinarily good' U.S. economic growth in 2021
text: Investor Mario Gabelli struck a positive note on Tuesday on the U.S. economy even as coronavirus cases in the country are on the rise.

title: The Tell: The ‘election premium' in the currency market is collapsing…just like it did in 2016, notes SocGen
text: Currency traders are growing relaxed about the potential for volatility in the aftermath of the Nov. 3 U.S. presidential election as Democratic challenger Joe Biden holds a wide lead over President Donald Trump -- but the market saw a very similar move in the runup to the 2016 election, notes one currency watcher.

title: Market Extra: Why stock-market investors are starting to focus on Biden's narrowing lead against Trump
text: Some Wall Street strategists make the case that two weeks shy of the Nov. 3 election, some narrowing of recent chances for a victory in the presidential race by former Vice President Joe Biden against incumbent Donald Trump is causing some pause among investors.

title: Stock Market Today: Glimmer of Stimulus Hope Gives Stocks a Small Lift
text: When is a deadline not a deadline? Apparently – and fortunately, for the stock market – when it relates to politicians passing a stimulus deal.

title: The GDP report next week will likely show record-breaking economic growth, but it may not help Trump
text: Next week, the U.S. will get economic news like it has never seen before, reflecting growth that had seemed impossible, as it is likely that GDP will have risen by more than 30%.

title: Stocks rebound to end higher on stimulus hopes, earnings
text: U.S. stocks closed higher Tuesday as investors remained optimistic about the prospects of additional fiscal aid from Washington. The Dow Jones Industrial Average added about 113 points, 0.4%, to close near 28,308, according to a preliminary reading, while the S&P 500 gained 16 points, 0.5%, closing near 3,443.

title: This is an income statement recession, not a balance sheet recession: #1 bank analyst
text: Mike Mayo, Wells Fargo managing director and senior banking analyst, joins 'Closing Bell' to discuss the bank and financial sector, why banks have underperformed this year and what it will take for the sector to improve its performance.

title: Market Extra: The unraveling of this popular bond-market trade shows investors believe U.S. recovery will outpace Europe once again
text: The widening gulf between U.S. and European bond markets could point to a reversal of Europe's fortunes in the eyes of Wall Street.

title: DeMark Analysis Points Higher Yet For S&P 500 and Nasdaq
text: The stock market continues to move higher in the face of a uniquely high amount of economic uncertainty. This is the very essence of investors climbing the “wall of worry.

title: Analysis: Betting on further U.S. yield curve steepening? Not so fast!
text: Investors betting that optimism over the U.S. economic outlook will lift yields on longer-term U.S. Treasury securities faster than short-term rates could be in for a major surprise.

title: Fed's Evans sees less economic drag from new COVID-19 wave
text: The current rise in COVID-19 infections in the United States may not dent the recovery too much, Chicago Federal Reserve Bank President Charles Evans said on Tuesday, adding that he remains "reasonably optimistic" U.S. unemployment will fall to 5.5% by the end of next year.

title: Fed's Evans says fiscal and health policies more important now than further central bank action
text: Fiscal and public-health policies would give a greater boost to the economy right now than any further action by the U.S. central bank might have, Chicago Fed President Charles Evans said Tuesday.

title: Nancy Pelosi optimistic about stimulus deal, stocks jump on optimism

title: How To Play The Digestion Phase
text: The near-term action continues to be driven by the state of additional stimulus.

title: Pelosi says she is 'optimistic' can reach COVID deal with White House
text: U.S. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi on Tuesday said she was optimistic Democrats could reach a deal with the Trump administration on additional COVID-19 relief that could get aid out by early next month.

title: Why this top-ranked macro strategist is still positive on equities
text: Marko Kolanovic, J.P. Morgan's global head of macro quant and derivatives strategy, joins CNBC's "Halftime Report" team to discuss how he views the market action.

title: The Technical Indicator: Charting a successful technical test, S&P 500 nails the breakout point
text: Technically speaking, the major U.S. benchmarks continue to digest an October breakout amid still bullish bigger-picture price action, writes Michael Ashbaugh.

title: Is the yield curve indicating a growing U.S. economy?
text: In order to get inflation going in an economy, the yield curve needs to go from steep to flat. title: Regulators begin to sift through wreckage of market's COVID-19 collapse for clues about what went wrong
text: Market regulators in the U.S. and around the world are starting to sift through the collapse of financial markets last March for clues about what went wrong and what needs to be fixed.

title: JPM's Normand: Markets Reflect Optimism of Big Stimulus by January
text: Oct.20 -- John Normand, head of cross asset fundamental strategy at JPMorgan, and his expectations for fourth-quarter U.S. economic growth. He speaks with Bloomberg's Tom Keene on “Bloomberg Surveillance.

title: BlackRock's Kosterich: Rates Can Tick Higher, But Not Melt Up
text: Oct.20 -- Russ Koesterich, portfolio manager at BlackRock Global Allocation Fund, discuses yields, interest rates, and signals from the bond market. He speaks on “Bloomberg Surveillance.

title: Is the Stock Market Getting Closer to a Big Decline?
text: The quick answer to that question is that investors need to see more evidence of underlying weakness in the stock market. That said, the time for a decline is growing near.

title: The Long Arc Of Justice Will Come For The Markets And Everything Else Too
text: I struggle with the current valuations, even as I believe in my investments for 10,000 days.

title: Market Extra: Peter Schiff, who predicted stock-market meltdown, readying defamation suit after report says his firm linked to money-laundering probe
text: A Puerto Rico-based financial institution founded by Peter Schiff, the chief executive of Euro Pacific Capital, and a market pundit who often espouses what critics describe as a bearish outlook for the market, is being investigated for tax evasion and money laundering, a report conducted jointly with the New York Times and The Age alleges in a report published on Monday.

title: KKR's McVey Says Markets Are Pricing In a Biden Victory
text: Oct.20 -- Henry McVey, head of global macro and asset allocation at KKR, says an increased antitrust crackdown on Big Tech poses a macro risk for markets and adds that investors have been pricing in a Joe Biden election victory. He speaks during an interview with Bloomberg's Erik Schatzker on "Bloomberg Markets."

title: Stock Market Swings Up and Down With Stimulus News
text: Investors continue to get whipped back and forth by U.S. government stimulus talks. The window for passing a bill before the election is ending, but there is still a chance… therefore, investors are monitoring every news flash regarding a potential stimulus bill.

title: Is the Stock Market Coming to a Head?
text: The hope that the stock market held onto coming into the week waned a bit on Monday as government stimulus talks stalled once again.  After the market close, more news headlines emerged as the Senate is back and both sides know that politically some stimulus package should be passed.

title: Housing Starts, Building Permits Positive but Tempered
text: Looking beneath this mild disappointment on Housing Starts, year over year single-family home ownership is up 24%.

title: Powell Says Federal Reserve Is Considering Proprietary Cryptocurrency
text: The Fed chief says it is weighing the many aspects of creating a central-bank digital currency.

title: Will Fed Underwrite Another Stimulus?
text: If Congress approves a second stimulus to mitigate the pandemic's economic fallout, will the Fed do another round of quantitative easing to absorb the debt?

title: US Indexes Close Lower Monday
text: The Dow Jones Industrial Average closed at 28,195.42 on Monday with a loss of 410.89 points or -1.44%. The S&P 500 closed at 3,426.92 for a loss of 56.89 points or -1.63%.

title: Wall Street opens higher with focus on stimulus
text: Wall Street's main indexes opened higher on Tuesday as investors were hopeful of more stimulus from Washington, with Senate Republicans preparing to vote on a bill to help small businesses hammered by the COVID-19 pandemic.

title: Dow gains at Tuesday's open as coronavirus relief package deadline and vaccines come into focus
text: U.S. stock benchmarks on Tuesday kicked off trade modestly higher, as stocks attempted to recover from the worst daily percentage decline in about a month. House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin have indicated that differences in negotiations toward a sweeping coronavirus aid package are "narrowing," with a self-imposed deadline of end of day Tuesday looming.

title: Economic Report: New-home construction rises modestly in September, driven by a Northeast building boom
text: While single-family housing starts have improved, the multifamily sector is struggling.

title: U.S. single-family homebuilding accelerates in September
text: U.S. single-family homebuilding surged in September, cementing the housing market's status as the star of the economic recovery, thanks to record-low interest rates and a migration to the suburbs and low-density areas as Americans seek more room for home offices and schooling.

title: Deadline Day: Fiscal Stimulus Showdown In Focus, With Netflix, Snap Results Up Later
text: Today looks like the final showdown for stimulus, and the market is a little jumpy. Volatility is down a bit but neared the top end of its recent range overnight.

title: U.S. housing starts total 1.415 million in September, vs 1.457 million expected
text: CNBC's Rick Santelli, Diana Olick and Steve Liesman join "Squawk Box" to break down the September read on housing starts and building permits.
